The Shattered Glass Sky:27:497:1.text:
The Shattered Glass Sky 
The sky is shattered — a mosaic of broken glass spread across the heavens. Each fragment holds its own firmament, with its own stars, suns, moons, and weather that never change. Beneath each sky lies a matching shard of earth: deserts burned into permanence beside tundras locked in endless frost. Along the great cracks, climates meet without blending. A traveler might take two steps — one into searing heat, the next into soft, unending rain.

The Shattered Glass Sky:499:718:2.text: The stars are not suns, but the souls of sorcerers who gambled against the Magemaker and lost. Nailed to the heavens, they burn in agony until their debt is paid, their light a reminder of the cost of heedless ambition.

The Shattered Glass Sky:720:775:3.text: The city of Ibnasi itself is beneath a three-way crack.

The Shattered Glass Sky:777:885:4.text:
Under a burning, white hot sun in eternal summer:  
Amber Market, Monastery, Old Ibnasi, The Lantern Quarter

The Shattered Glass Sky:887:1019:5.text:
Under clear blue skies, with a calm breeze and a comfortable warmth: 
The Sprawl, The Institute, The Counting House, the Cedar Court

The Shattered Glass Sky:1021:1075:6.text: Under rainy. stormy skies with occasional, foggy calm:

The Shattered Glass Sky:1077:1119:7.text: The Necropolis, The Guildhouse, The Harbor

The Ratways:47:540:2.text:
Description:
The Ratways are an immense subterranean network of corridors made of green-black metal, carved into perfect geometric form. They are older than recorded history — older, some claim, than life itself. No one knows who made them or why. Every angle, junction, and corridor is precise; the structure is entirely deterministic. There are no random paths, no shifting walls, and no apparent end. Every unique sequence of turns corresponds to a fixed point somewhere in the world above.

The Ratways:542:977:3.text: A person walking the Ratways does not wander so much as execute a sequence. The geometry itself is constant and absolute. Following a specific pattern of turns leads to a single location on the surface — a desert hollow, a mountain cave, a pit beneath a ruined city. Because the pathways never change, these sequences can be mapped, recorded, and traded. Accurate maps of known routes are among the most valuable possessions in Ibnasi.

The Ratways:979:1518:4.text: Travel through the Ratways is the work of Pathfinders, a professional class of sorcerers who have learned to use the system as transportation and trade infrastructure. A Pathfinder walks to a chosen coordinate, then performs a simple, personal gesture with their token — a small, valuable object bound to them. Examples include slipping on a ring, tying a string, or closing a locket. The moment the action is completed, the world around them shifts seamlessly and instantly, and they find themselves at the corresponding surface location.

The Ratways:1520:1849:5.text: The token is not magical in the traditional sense. It acts as an anchor — a reference point the Ratways use to locate and return the traveler. When the Pathfinder undoes the action (removing the ring, untying the string, opening the locket), the world snaps back, and they stand once more in the green-black halls of the Ratways.

The City of Ibnasi:22:56:1.text: Name: Ibnasi, The City Under Stars

The City of Ibnasi:98:269:3.text:
Description:
A massive, sprawling, coastal city;  the largest in the world. It's divided into 10 districts. Urban sprawl causes the buildings to spill out past city walls.

The City of Ibnasi:271:419:4.text: It is situated right underneath a crack, making it so that the North and East of the city is cool and pleasant, and the South and West are very hot.

The City of Ibnasi:421:470:5.text: Contains 10 districts, each with its own purpose.

The City of Ibnasi:472:1249:6.text:
Districts:
1. The Amber Market sits at the center of old Ibnasi, on hot, limestone bricks. It’s a vast open-air sprawl of stalls, pavilions, and carts — a blanket of color and noise under a harsh sky. The air is thick with the mingled smells of spice, incense, grilled meat, herbs, medicine, animals, and sweat. The sound never stops: hawkers calling, bartering voices clashing, carts creaking, footsteps grinding dust into the ground.
At the very center of it all rises The Counting House, a tall, narrow, decorated, curved brick tower that points upward like needle poking the sky. It serves as the market’s anchor and the city’s oldest landmark, marking the original heart around which Ibnasi once grew in concentric walls before spilling beyond them into the modern sprawl.

The City of Ibnasi:1251:2015:7.text: 2.  The Harbor unfolds beneath the city like a restless sea of masts and canvas. Great galleons, lean couriers, and weathered fishing boats drift together in the slow churn of tide and trade. The air is thick with salt, pitch, and the call of gulls. At the mouth of the bay rise two colossal tusks of Moonbone, narrow at their roots and curving upward until their tips nearly touch, leaving a slender gap where the sky peers through. They gleam faintly even under cloud, and when night falls, they catch the moonlight as though it were their native element. Beyond the arch, the sea stretches vast and dark, and far past it—beyond the reach of the waves—stands the great lighthouse, its fire sweeping across the water like a steady heartbeat guiding the city home.

The City of Ibnasi:2017:2502:8.text: 3. Near Ibnasi’s eastern gate stands the Monastery of the Seven Stars — a vast dome of red clay and black iron that burns crimson in the morning light. The dome is punctured with precise, star-shaped holes so that, at dawn and dusk, constellations drift across the interior walls in moving patterns of gold. Inside, the floor lies beneath a film of clear water, shallow enough to walk but deep enough to shimmer. Every sound — footstep, whisper, chant — folds back upon itself in echo.

The City of Ibnasi:2504:2983:9.text: At the heart of the monastery gapes the Pit: a perfect circle descending into endless shadow. Its walls are carved with narrow stairs spiraling into the dark, each step worn smooth by centuries of descent. Each night, the priests of the Seven Stars walk down those steps bearing lanterns, their light dimming one by one as they vanish below. The faithful gather around the rim, murmuring prayers as they cast offerings — grain, fruit, incense, crafted trinkets — into the depths.

The City of Ibnasi:2985:4297:10.text:
4.Near the counting house stands the Governmental Complex, known formally as The Cedar Court. This vast wooden edifice rises over the city, its surface carved with patterns of myth and lineage. The central hall serves as the city's senate, with walls and ceiling fashioned from ancient teak and cedar timber. A coffered ceiling stretches high above, each panel etched with designs that cast layered shadows through warm light.
The complex unfolds in terraces of offset cubes, each level set back from the one below. These cubes are leased by Houses of the city—merchant dynasties, old bloodlines, and newly risen names alike. Their offices open onto private courtyards and balconies, with higher cubes representing greater wealth and influence.
Terraces brim with flowering vines, citrus trees, and banners of deep colors. The Council Hall lies at the complex's core, governed by the Council of Five—the city's rulers and law interpreters. Their offices overlook a central garden where Houses gather to vote on decrees.
The garden features jasmine, roses, and a stone fish pond with lotus blooms. Inside, the air carries aged wood and fine oils. Polished teak floors show centuries of passage, while records rest on cedar desks. Warm lamplight seeps through lattice screens, casting shadows during deliberations.

The City of Ibnasi:4299:5556:11.text:
5. In the Lantern Quarter, beneath a velvet sky pricked with stars, the entertainment district winds through narrow streets paved with stones that shimmer faintly in the lanternlight, as if the city itself bled through an open wound. The buildings rise three and four stories high, their red brick and white plaster softened by the glow of paper lights strung between balconies of painted wood.
Music seeps from the pleasure houses, each melody bleeding into the next until the whole quarter hums like a living instrument. The air is thick with the scent of spiced wine, roasted meat, and perfume drifting from open windows. Smoke curls lazily from the lounges where patrons recline on cushions, their laughter mingling with the low pluck of lutes and the whisper of silk garments brushing together.
Down below, the gambling halls burn with gold light. Oil lamps flicker in shuttered rooms, casting amber pools across dice tables and the faces of players bent over their fortunes. Iron lanterns sway in the night breeze, their shadows breathing over the walls. Beneath the constellation-lit sky, the Lantern Quarter pulses with the life of nocturnal trade—vendors calling softly, lovers wandering arm in arm, and the occasional drunkard serenading the moon.

The City of Ibnasi:5558:5912:12.text: 6. Old Ibnasi, the oldest section of the city, abandoned when the wealthy built newer districts and moved away. The buildings here are made of simple stone and clay, with wooden shutters that hang loose on rusted hinges and tile roofs that have collapsed in places. Moss grows thick on the north-facing walls, and wild vines cover many of the structures.

The City of Ibnasi:5914:6238:13.text: The smell is of damp stone, old mortar, and the sweet scent of wild herbs that have grown wild in the abandoned courtyards. Empty windows frame nothing but darkness and the soft sound of wind through broken roof tiles. The streets themselves are paved with old stones that have shifted and cracked, creating uneven walkways.

The City of Ibnasi:6240:6641:14.text: Only a few dozen people still live here — the very poor who can afford the cheap rent, and those who prefer to live where no one asks questions. They have made homes in the surviving buildings, patching windows with boards and hanging blankets over doorways. During the day, people can be found rummaging through the ruins for salvage: usable stones, old ironwork, anything that can be sold or reused.

The City of Ibnasi:6643:9225:15.text:
7. The Greys
A city within the city, The Greys rise from the eastern roads in a vast sweep of dark stone and iron shadow. Every building here is carved from the same deep grey granite, its surfaces worked with repeating geometric patterns — spirals, knots, latticework — sharp-edged and patient, catching stray light in their grooves. Black iron ribs brace the stained-glass windows that bloom across the façades in panes of cobalt, amber, and wine-red. When the sun shifts, those colors scatter across the stone walkways in trembling shards, brief glimmers against the district’s quiet austerity.
The Greys feel enormous even when nearly empty. Long hallways stretch past rows of iron sconces; vaulted galleries echo with only a handful of footsteps. Skybridges run between towers like arteries, their iron frames groaning softly in the wind. Brass pipes thread the walls in thick bundles, carrying water, pressure, and heat to the workshops below. They pulse with faint warmth when touched, humming like the heartbeat of some enormous stone organism.
The district was built for far more scholars than inhabit it now. Lecture halls that could seat hundreds host a dozen at most. Reading rooms stand half-lit, their long tables occupied by solitary figures in grey robes. Workrooms glow from only one or two windows, the rest falling into shadow. This undercurrent of emptiness does not feel abandoned — only disciplined, as though the quiet itself were part of the study.
The Institute lies at the district’s core: a cluster of interconnected towers, courtyards, and chambers where healers, alchemists, artificers, translators, and scholars work in parallel. In the Healing Halls, sunlight falls through colored glass onto stone basins and herb racks; in the alchemical courts, brass coils hiss with escaping steam; in the artificer’s ranges, the steady clang of metal rings against the vaulted ceilings.
Yet the noise never spreads. Sound dies quickly here, swallowed by the heavy stone and high arches. Even in its busiest pockets, the Greys maintain their quiet gravity. The district feels as though it’s holding its breath — patient, focused, carved into permanence. A place where thought is not performed, but honed. Where knowledge is a craft. Where silence is a tool.
Walking its corridors, one feels the weight of an older ambition — a district raised in confidence, now inhabited by the few who continue its work with slow, steady dedication. The Greys endure, not as relic or monument, but as a living engine running at a low, constant hum beneath its stained-glass glow.

The City of Ibnasi:9227:10270:16.text:
8. Beyond the outer wall lies the Sprawl, the newest and widest reach of Ibnasi. It formed when the city’s second ring filled to its edges and builders pressed outward, raising homes and workshops beyond the old boundary. Like the rings of a tree, each wall marks an age of Ibnasi’s growth, and the Sprawl is the youngest layer.
The roads are broad and clean, paved with granite that still shows the marks of recent chiseling. Houses are built with clay-plated roofs, plaster walls, and wooden beams. Courtyards hold young trees, and irrigation channels carry clear water from the city aqueduct. The air smells of lime, dust, and freshly cut wood.
Though distant from the heart, the Sprawl remains under Ibnasi’s law and watch. Guards patrol its gates, tax collectors make their rounds, and lanterns burn each night along the main roads. It is a district of ambition and restlessness, where trade grows quickly and families seek new beginnings. The Sprawl stands as Ibnasi’s living edge: not a ruin beyond the wall, but the city’s next breath.

The City of Ibnasi:10272:12366:17.text:
9. The Soots is a dense thicket of workshops, all pressed close together so that roofs overlap and chimneys rise in uneven clusters. The streets here run narrow, paved with flat stone worn smooth by years of foot traffic and cart wheels. Thin lines of sawdust gather in the cracks, and curls of wood shavings drift out of open doorways like autumn leaves.
From dawn onward, the air trembles with work. Hammers strike metal in steady rhythms that bounce between the walls. The rasp of files, the clatter of tools, the soft thud of carved wood falling onto benches — all of it layers together into a constant, living noise. Smoke curls from chimneys in light, steady threads, mixing with the scent of hot iron, shaved cedar, binding glue, and dye.
Inside the open-front workshops, lamps burn low during the day to help craftsmen see the fine details: a line of grain in a timber, the edge of a blade, the color shift in cooling glass. Racks of tools line the walls — chisels, mallets, clamps, tongs — each marked by years of use. Some floors are covered in sawdust, others in straw or stone; every shop has its own texture.
Between the workshops, narrow alleys branch like capillaries. Here, apprentices hurry past with crates, bundles of rods, unfinished lantern frames, coils of wire, and baskets of nails. The smell changes with every few steps: hot resin, fresh-cut wood, oil, dye, the faint sweetness of heated brass.
Above the ground level, wooden walkways and small balconies jut outward, dotted with drying cloth, stacked crates, and tool racks. Many families live directly above their craft rooms. In the late afternoon, open windows let spill the scent of meals cooking and the sound of low conversation drifting over the noise of work.
Despite its name, the Soots is not dark or grim. Sunlight slips between the rooftops and catches the floating dust motes, turning them gold. The chimneys release only thin smoke, rising straight in the warm air. And at dusk, when the workshops shutter their doors, the district glows softly with the light of forge embers cooling behind brick walls.

The City of Ibnasi:12368:12679:18.text: 10. The Necropolis  is located on the city's north side where cooler air flows in, this cemetery covers several blocks of well-maintained grounds with monuments of local stone and marble. The pathways are paved with fitted flagstones, and iron lanterns mounted on stone posts provide light along the main walks.

The City of Ibnasi:12681:13030:19.text: The air here carries the clean scent of cut stone, old flowers, and the polish used on the monuments. Flower vendors set up carts at the main entrance, selling fresh blooms and dried arrangements to visitors who come to tend family graves. The grounds are quiet except for the soft murmur of prayers and the measured footsteps of the groundskeepers.

The City of Ibnasi:13032:13445:20.text: Several families maintain full-time caretakers who live in small houses within the cemetery, tending the grounds and maintaining the monuments. Their daily work involves cleaning the headstones, tending the small gardens around family plots, and replacing the flowers that visitors leave. The smell of fresh-cut flowers and stone dust mingles with the polish and oil used to keep the monuments looking their best.

The City of Ibnasi:13447:13864:21.text: Families visit regularly to tend their plots, bringing fresh flowers and maintaining the small memorial gardens around their relatives' graves. During major holidays, the cemetery fills with people visiting relatives' graves, and the quiet grounds become busy with respectful visitors. Children sometimes accompany their parents to learn about ancestors, moving quietly between the monuments while their elders work.
